36.816628175519625

The remaining attributes are either binary or categorical (e.g. Title, Culture, mother etc.) such that, it would be pointless to substitute the nulls with the mode or by implementing KNN.

The only numerical attributes left unhandled are dateOfBirth and DateoFdeath.

Any kind of substitution of null values in the dateOfBirth attribute could result in inconsistency with the attribute age.

DateoFDeath signifies whether a character is still alive or not. We could be very wrong if we use, for example, KNN to substitute the null values.

Therefore, we will create a new category which will denote missing data - Unknown.

In [518]:
df = df.fillna('Unknown')

1.4. Dimensionality reduction with PCA¶

In [422]:
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from mpl_toolkits.mplot3d import Axes3D

fig = plt.figure(figsize=(8, 6))
ax = Axes3D(fig, elev=-150, azim=110)

colors = ['navy', 'turquoise', 'darkorange']

pca = PCA(n_components=3) #We set the number of components to 3 so we can transform to a 3D space
X_reduced = pca.fit(X).transform(X) # Now we fit the PCA model to X with fit() and apply it to X immediately with transform() 
ax.scatter(X_reduced[:, 0], X_reduced[:, 1], X_reduced[:, 2], c=y, edgecolor='k', s=40)
ax.set_title("First three PCA directions")
ax.set_xlabel("1st eigenvector")
ax.set_ylabel("2nd eigenvector")
ax.set_zlabel("3rd eigenvector")
ax.w_xaxis.set_ticklabels([])
ax.w_yaxis.set_ticklabels([])
ax.w_zaxis.set_ticklabels([])
plt.show()
In [423]:
pca = PCA(n_components=2) #We set the number of components to 2 so we can transform to a 2D space
X_PCA = pca.fit(X).transform(X) # We again fit the PCA model to X with fit() and apply it to X immediately with transform() 

plt.figure() #Since we only have 2 dimensions we can now draw the data to a 2D space using the same method from above (scatter)
for color, i, target_name in zip(colors, [0, 1, 2], ['Alive', 'Dead']):
    plt.scatter(X_PCA[y == i, 0], X_PCA[y == i, 1], color=color, alpha=.8, lw=2,
                label=target_name)
plt.legend(loc='best', shadow=False, scatterpoints=1)
plt.title('PCA of GoT dataset')
plt.show()
In [424]:
lda = LinearDiscriminantAnalysis(n_components=1) #We set the number of components to 2 so we can transform to a 2D space
X_LDA = lda.fit(X, y).transform(X) # We fit the LDA model to X,y with fit() and apply it to X immediately with transform() 
#Note that in LDA, we also give class information when fitting the model since it is a supervised method unlike PCA
plt.figure() #We can again draw the data to a 2D space
for color, i, target_name in zip(colors, [0, 1], ['Alive', 'Dead']):
    plt.scatter(X_LDA[y == i, 0], X_LDA[y == i, 0], alpha=.8, color=color,
                label=target_name)
plt.legend(loc='best', shadow=False, scatterpoints=1)
plt.title('LDA of GoT dataset')

In [479]:
#We can't use Gaussian version of Naive Bayes since not all of the attributes are continuous

#Instead, we can try Bernulli version of NB, because many of the attributes in the dataset are binary.
#Moreover, with OneHotEncoder being implemented to the dataset, the majority of the attributes are binary.
#In this case, Bernulli NB's assumption of binary-valued features will be pretty much correct

from sklearn.naive_bayes import BernoulliNB

bnb = BernoulliNB()
bnb.fit(X_train, Y_train)
y_pred = bnb.predict(X_test)

2.3.3. Complement NB¶

In [487]:
#The Complement NB is an adaptation of the Multinomial NB algorithm that is particularly suited for imbalanced data sets.


from sklearn.naive_bayes import ComplementNB

cnb = ComplementNB()
cnb.fit(X_train, Y_train)
